			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2015</a> keynote:</span><br><i>What’s the value of an end user? Platforms and Research: The case of Pharo and Moose</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/StéphaneDucasse.html">Stéphane Ducasse</a></h2>
<ul><li>URL: <a href="https://www.sleconf.org/2015/Papers#keynote">https://www.sleconf.org/2015/Papers#keynote</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagM">T4A: Workbenches</span></a><ul><li> The keynote is explicitly about building and evolving research platforms (language + analysis platform) as language-engineering infrastructure.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3d.html"><span class="tagL">T3D: GPLs</span></a><ul><li> Pharo is a general-purpose programming language platform, and language/platform design is a recurring theme.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagL">T5B: Language Description Analysis</span></a><ul><li> Moose is fundamentally about program/software analysis, and several cited results revolve around analyzing code and histories.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t2b.html"><span class="tagL">T2B: Evolution</span></a><ul><li> Topics like dynamic core updates and (especially) automated migration-rule generation are directly about evolution and maintenance over time.
</li></ul></li></ul>
